Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 2000, the U.S. presidential election was ruled inconclusive as only 537 votes in Florida separated Al Gore and George W. Bush.

The election was a tumultuous process, starting with confusion on election night as networks first declared Florida for Gore, then for Bush, and back again, before Gore retracted his concession.

Despite Gore winning the popular vote by over 500,000 votes, the Electoral College ultimately decided the outcome. The recounts and legal challenges in Florida became a national spectacle, with terms like "hanging chads" and "dimpled chads" becoming widely recognized. The controversial butterfly ballot design in Florida, which led to misvotes, compounded the problem.

The recount process was marred by inconsistent standards and legal battles, culminating in a decision by the U.S. Supreme Court. The Court ruled 7-2 that the recount violated constitutional standards for consistency, and by a 5-4 vote, stopped the recount due to time constraints, effectively awarding Florida—and thus the presidency—to Bush.

The ruling, which divided along ideological lines, remains one of the most controversial in American history. Bush won the election despite losing the popular vote, making him the first president since 1888 to do so.

Name: Alford, Mark
text:
The anchor represents a universal message of safety, hope, and strength.

Today at the Veterans Cemetery in Higginsville, we were honored to speak at the dedication of a Sea Service Memorial that features this strong symbol.

The memorial will honor our great sailors and marines after they navigated the unpredictable seas of life.

One of the veterans in attendance today was C. W. Hook, a World War II veteran and true patriot.

Name: Gillibrand, Kirsten E.
text:
I am honored to have won re-election, and promise to continue to work toward bipartisan solutions for New Yorkers.

Our state—and what we accomplished here—brings me hope.

We passed Proposition 1, enshrining equal rights in our state’s constitution. We built an unprecedented coordinated campaign—our state’s first-ever. Our team and volunteers knocked on 1.3 million doors, called 4.7 million voters, and turned out voters across the state’s seven battleground districts. We successfully defended all our Democratic incumbents in NY and flipped three seats blue. The New York State congressional delegation will send four more Democrats to Washington than the last Congress.

These victories make clear that New Yorkers believe in finding common sense solutions to the very real challenges we face, from getting costs down and wages up to keeping our communities safe.

We believe in fundamental truths like caring for our neighbors and treating others with kindness, decency and respect.

I promise to stand shoulder-to-shoulder with you in this work.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1895, physicist Wilhelm Conrad Röntgen discovered X-rays while experimenting with cathode rays in his lab in Germany. 

Noticing a glow from a nearby screen, he identified the unknown rays and named them X-rays. These electromagnetic waves, much shorter than visible light, could penetrate soft tissue but were blocked by denser materials like bone. Röntgen's discovery revolutionized medicine by allowing doctors to view the inside of the human body without surgery. X-rays were first used in military medicine during the Balkan War of 1897 to locate bullets and fractures.

Though initially seen as harmless, the dangers of X-ray radiation became apparent in the early 1900s after reports of burns and skin damage, and the death of Thomas Edison's assistant from cancer. Despite these risks, X-rays were used in various consumer products, like shoe-fitting fluoroscopes, until the 1950s, when their dangers were better understood. Röntgen, who received the first Nobel Prize in Physics in 1901 for his discovery, never patented X-rays. Today, X-ray technology is widely used in medicine, security, and materials testing.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share the remarkable stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district—individuals who rise above the ordinary and inspire us all. Today, we honor the life and legacy of an extraordinary woman who touched countless lives in our community, a true Hometown Hero—Tina Marie Grady of Morrisville, whom we sadly lost a few weeks ago.

Tina’s life was a powerful testament to resilience, boundless compassion, and the extraordinary impact one person can have on the lives of others. Her 33 years of sobriety fueled her mission to become a beacon of hope and help for those struggling in our community. She was often the first to speak up and advocate for those facing addiction and mental health challenges, offering them unwavering support and reminding them that brighter days were possible. Tina provided invaluable hope and inspiration to so many, showing them they were never alone on their journey.

Her compassion for others shone most brightly through her passion for Christmas, a holiday she infused with purpose. She founded Evan’s Army Children Without  Parents, an organization named in honor of her late son, Evan, with the vision to bring the magic of Christmas to children who had lost a parent to addiction or suicide, ensuring they had the opportunity to experience the joy of Christmas morning—and she did just that. Just last year alone, Tina’s efforts brought Christmas joy to nearly 500 children, making sure that each of them felt loved and remembered.

Tina’s commitment did not stop with the holiday season. She worked year-round to ensure these children felt supported and valued, raising funds, gathering resources, and rallying the community to help them thrive. Under her leadership, Children Without Parents ~ Evan’s Army grew to become one of the largest toy drives and nonprofits in our area—a powerful testament to her tireless dedication and unbreakable spirit.

As co-chair of the Bipartisan Mental Health and Substance Use Disorder Task Force, I had the profound honor of working alongside Tina and witnessing firsthand the incredible impact of her life’s work. Her passion for helping families and children affected by mental health and substance use crises went beyond dedication—it was a calling. Her warmth, compassion, and drive to make a difference inspired everyone who crossed her path, including me. 

Today, let us honor Tina’s memory by carrying her mission forward, remembering the love she brought to our community and the lives she changed for the better. Please join me in extending our condolences to Tina’s parents, Sam and Alison; her husband, William; her five children; her seven grandchildren; and all who loved her—she will never be forgotten, and her impact will be felt forever.

text:

Disasters like the Camp Fire cannot become the norm. As these wildfires grow more frequent and severe, we must push for aggressive forest management and common-sense policies to help reduce risk. I remain dedicated to passing the Federal Disaster Tax Relief Act to ease the financial burdens on survivors as they rebuild. The road to recovery is long, but together we will continue to take action to protect our homes, businesses, and most importantly, our people from this preventable threat.

Name: Harris, Andy
text:
As we approach Veterans Day, here are helpful resources for Veterans in my district passed on to my office from the Social Security Administration (SSA). 

✔️Disability Benefits: Veterans who have a Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) disability compensation rating of 100% Permanent & Total (P&T) can receive expedited processing of their Social Security disability claims. 
Read about the difference between SSA and VA disability benefits in SSA’s publication, Social Security Disability and Veterans Affairs - How Do They Compare? Link: https://t.co/cjOps9dnsP

✔️Supplemental Security Income (SSI): Aged or disabled veterans with limited income and resources may be eligible for SSI, which provides financial assistance to meet basic needs. 

✔️Employment Tools: SSA’s publication, Journey to Success: Employment Tools for Veterans with Disabilities, offers valuable resources such as career counseling, job training, and employment services to help veterans. Link: https://t.co/bXKQp2ekO8

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First 

Wayne Bray, a resident of Williamston, NC, has dedicated his life to serving veterans. A retired human resources professional with 25 years of experience, Wayne was a veteran representative at NC Works, helping veterans find jobs and secure benefits. He now serves part-time as a veterans service officer in Chowan County.

Since 2003, Wayne has been deeply involved with AMVETS, where he helps organize events like Veterans Day ceremonies, Memorial Day observances, and the Blue Christmas program, which raises awareness of veteran suicide. He coordinates care packages for veterans in nursing homes and leads a monthly prayer breakfast. Wayne's passion for serving veterans extends to his role in the American Legion, where he participates in quarterly Buddy Checks to ensure veterans are supported.

Wayne’s tireless volunteer work is a lifeline for veterans in eastern NC, providing much-needed resources and support while ensuring they are never forgotten.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
If we do not stand up to the International Criminal Court now, America is next.

If media reports are accurate, this is welcome news. There is a serious cloud hanging over Prosecutor Khan and his conduct regarding Israel and beyond. The allegations against him are serious and they must be investigated by an outside group to ensure a fair outcome for all. 

The decision to apply for arrest warrants against the Israeli Prime Minister and Minister of Defense without consultation with Israel is not only a violation of the letter and spirit of the Rome Statute, it raises serious questions as to why the planned consultation was canceled in the first place. 

The International Criminal Court has chosen the right path by allowing a new set of eyes to investigate and I would urge the Assembly to suspend Prosecutor Khan until the outcome of this investigation is finalized and issued to the public.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1989, East German officials opened the Berlin Wall, allowing free travel between East and West Berlin. The next day, jubilant crowds began tearing the wall down. 

This marked the collapse of one of the Cold War's most infamous symbols, as the wall's destruction was quickly followed by souvenir hunters collecting pieces of rubble. The decision to open the wall was influenced by Hungary's recent move to open its border with Austria, allowing East Germans to bypass the Berlin Wall entirely and escape to the West. 

The fall of the wall also reflected broader political shifts in East Germany, where the communist regime was losing power and calls for democratic reforms grew louder. The event had a significant impact on U.S. President George Bush and his advisors, who, after watching the celebrations on television, grew more convinced that Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev’s reformist stance was genuine. Unlike past Soviet crackdowns in Hungary (1956) and Czechoslovakia (1968), Gorbachev supported the changes in East Germany, signaling a shift in Soviet policy. The fall of the Berlin Wall was a key moment in the Cold War's decline.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
That was a cataclysm. Electoral map wipeout. Senate D practical ceiling is now 52 seats. R's is 62.

Time to rebuild the left.

We are out of touch with the crisis of meaning/purpose fueling MAGA. We refuse to pick big fights. Our tent is too small.

1/ Some early thoughts:

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 3/ The things that mattered are disappearing. We spend half as much time with friends as a generation ago. Hard work no longer guarantees economic mobility. Institutions (like churches) are delegitimized. Place based identity evaporates as we all become "global citizens."

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 2/ The left has never fully grappled with the wreckage of fifty years of neoliberalism, which has left legions of Americans adrift as local places are hollowed out, rapacious profit seeking cannibalizes the common good, and unchecked new technology separates and isolates us.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 4/ The left skips past the way people are feeling (alone, impotent, overwhelmed) and straight to uninspiring solutions (more roads! bulk drug purchasing!) that do little to actually upset the status quo of who has power and who doesn't.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 5/ Does racism explain part of the attraction of the right's nativism? Of course. But mass deportation is a (terrible) response to Americans' real sense they are helpless in the face of global forces (like increased migration). The left largely ignores this pain.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 7/ Meanwhile, men tumble into a different kind of identity crisis, as the patriarchy, society's primary organizing paradigm for centuries, rightly crashes. The right pushes an alluring dial back. The left says "get over it". Again, a refusal to listen/offer responsible solutions.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
6/ We don't listen enough; we tell people what's good for them.

And when progressives like Bernie aggressively go after the elites that hold people down, they are shunned as dangerous populists. Why? Maybe because true economic populism is bad for our high-income base. 😬

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 8/ We cannot be afraid of fights - especially with the economic elites who have profited off neoliberalism. The right regularly picks fights with elites - Hollywood, higher ed, etc. Democrats (e.g. the Harris campaign) are tepid in our fights with billionaires and corporations.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
9/ Real economic populism should be our tentpole. 

But here's the thing - then you need to let people into the tent who aren't 100% on board with us on every social and cultural issue, or issues like guns or climate.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
10/ Those are hard things for the left. 

A firm break with neoliberalism.

Listen to poor and rural people, men in crisis. Don't decide for them.

Pick fights. Embrace populism.

Build a big tent. Be less judgmental.

But we are beyond small fixes.

text:
#MountainFire Update: The fire is currently at 20,640 acres with 26% containment. Mutual Aid resources from all over California continue to help with fighting this fire. 

There was minimal growth outside the containment line. Fire continues to creep and smolder in steep rugged terrain within receptive dry vegetation. 

Crews will take advantage of the light winds and humidity levels to continue work throughout the area. Damage inspection teams remain out in the fire area assessing affected structures.

Residents are encouraged to visit https://t.co/q1yPDbjUpa for the most current evacuation information. 

A community meeting will be held tonight, Sunday, November 10th, 2024, at 6 PM at Ventura County Fire Station 54, located at 2160 Pickwick Drive, Camarillo. The team will share incident updates and important information with the public.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1918, World War I ended when Germany, exhausted and on the brink of invasion, signed an armistice with the Allies in Compiégne, France.

The war’s roots trace back to June 28, 1914, when Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary was assassinated by a Bosnian Serb nationalist. This event escalated tensions between Austria-Hungary and Serbia, with Austria-Hungary blaming the Serbian government for the attack. Russia, allied with Serbia, mobilized its forces, prompting Austria-Hungary to declare war on Serbia on July 28, 1914. The conflict quickly spread as Germany supported Austria-Hungary, while France and Russia aligned against them. Germany's invasion of Belgium led to Britain declaring war on Germany.

The war, initially expected to be short, devolved into a brutal stalemate, especially on the Western Front, where trench warfare caused massive casualties. In 1915, the Allies tried to break the deadlock with a failed invasion of Turkey. By 1916, heavy offensives on the Western Front achieved no decisive results, though Germany had more success in the east, leading to a collapse of the Russian army and the Russian Revolution of 1917. By the end of 1917, the Bolsheviks had taken power and negotiated peace with Germany.

In 1918, the entry of American troops and resources tipped the balance in favor of the Allies. Germany, facing defeat, signed an armistice on November 11. The war, known as the “war to end all wars,” caused unimaginable destruction, resulting in about 9 million military deaths, 21 million wounded, and at least 5 million civilian casualties due to disease, starvation, and exposure. However, the Treaty of Versailles in 1919 imposed harsh terms on Germany, sowing the seeds for future conflict and leading to World War II.

Today and every day, we vow to uphold our sacred promise: just as we leave no soldier behind on the battlefield, we leave no veteran behind when they come home.

It is because of the bravery and sacrifice of our military, our veterans and their families that America is the land of the free.

Name: Ellzey, Jake
text:
Veterans Day always makes me stop and think about the Privilege, Service, and Sacrifice of our veterans. Every service member has a unique story, but we all share one thing in common: the privilege of serving this great country. We raised our right hands, swore an oath, and gave a part of ourselves to defend and protect the freedoms we hold dear. And we did it willingly, knowing full well that service would ask a lot from us—and our families.

The sacrifices of military life are different for each person, but they’re no less real. For me, as a Navy guy, service meant long hours on the flight line, days spent getting ready for missions that would take me into the sky or out on the water. There were plenty of thrills, but there were also the long hours of prepping and debriefing, making sure every part of the aircraft was good to go, and taking care of the young sailors who worked hard to make it all happen. Every mission, every day, was a reminder that service isn’t just about the big moments—it’s about the daily grind and the commitment to something bigger than yourself.

Today is a day to say “thank you” to all those who served, who made it through and came back home to build their lives alongside the rest of us. For me, that means spending time with my wife and kids, enjoying the freedoms our veterans fought for and making up for some of the time I missed while I was standing watch.

So, if you see a veteran today, take a minute to thank them. For what they did, for who they defended, and for the country they served.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Among the many special community celebrations this we attended throughout weekend, I was especially touched by the Veterans Day Ceremony & Reception at Central Bucks East, hosted by the inspiring students of Operation Eternal Gratitude. This student-led organization exemplifies patriotism and respect, dedicating their time to honoring the tremendous sacrifices of our Veterans and their families. Founded in the wake of 9/11, OEG reminds us all that the service of our veterans is foundational to our freedom and security.

Seeing young leaders step up to honor our Veterans is truly uplifting. Through initiatives like their Wall of Honor and partnerships with the Travis Manion Foundation, these students unite our community in gratitude for those who have served.

My deepest thanks to the teachers and mentors guiding these remarkable students, to OEG for your dedication to our community’s heroes, and to the Veterans we honor today and every day—we thank you, we honor you, and we are immensely grateful.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1966, astronaut Buzz Aldrin made history by taking the first-ever space selfie during the Gemini 12 mission, three years before his iconic moon landing. The Gemini 12 mission, aimed at refining techniques for a lunar landing, involved Aldrin and James Lovell performing critical tasks like extravehicular activities (EVAs) and spacecraft docking.

During his spacewalk, Aldrin set up his camera on the hatch of the spacecraft, aiming it at himself and capturing a photo with Earth in the background. This marked the first self-portrait taken in space. Aldrin lifted his helmet visor to allow his face to appear in the shot, despite the challenges posed by the bulky spacesuit and zero-gravity environment.

This historic selfie was made possible by specialized space photography equipment, designed to withstand space's extreme conditions. Aldrin's achievement paved the way for future space selfies, with astronauts like Donald Pettit and Stephen Robinson continuing the trend in the 2000s.

Aldrin’s selfie remains a key milestone in space photography, providing a personal connection to the broader narrative of space exploration.

Veterans Day allows Americans from all walks of life to recognize the tremendous sacrifices made by those who have risked their lives to defend freedom and democracy. To honor our veterans, we are proud to co-sponsor the following three bipartisan bills:

▪️H.R. 6373, the Veterans STAND Act,  to direct the Secretary of Veterans Affairs to offer annual preventative health evaluations to veterans with a spinal cord injury or disorder and increase access to assistive technologies.

▪️H.R. 7434, the BEST for Vets Act of 2024, to provide that only health care professionals who are licensed and not barred from practice may furnish medical disability examinations under the Department of Veterans Affairs pilot program related to using contract physicians for disability examinations. 

▪️H.R. 9324, the Protecting Veteran Access to Telemedicine Services Act of 2024, a bill giving medical professionals the authority to dispense certain covered medications during a telehealth appointment, easing the burden for disabled veterans and others for whom it is difficult to travel for an in-person appointment.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
I had the honor of reconnecting with Mykola Melnyk, Company Commander of the 47th Mechanized Brigade of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, whom I first met last August while celebrating Ukrainian Independence Day with our local Ukrainian-American community.

Mykola’s courage is nothing short of extraordinary. During Ukraine’s counter-offensive in Zaporizhzhia Oblast, he was gravely wounded—losing one leg to a Russian artillery strike and sustaining severe damage to the other after stepping on two anti-personnel mines. Despite these near-fatal injuries, he continues to defy the odds, standing strong as he prepares to head back to Ukraine next week and resume the fight for freedom.

The Ukrainian people have shown the world what it truly means to fight for sovereignty and democracy. As they stand firm against tyranny, we must continue to stand with them. Mykola’s bravery is a testament to their resolve and a reminder that Ukraine’s fight is a fight for all who cherish freedom and the very principles that define the American way. Slava Ukraini! 🇺🇸🇺🇦

Name: Letlow, Julia
text:
Tonight, I urge my colleagues to vote in support of H.R. 82 the #SocialSecurityFairnessAct.

The unfair provisions of WEP and GPO impact our public servants — the teachers who educate our children and the firefighters and police officers who keep our communities safe. Our public servants deserve their hard-earned retirement benefits. 

It is time to right this wrong.

Name: Sessions, Pete
text:
Last week, a former FEMA employee told a hurricane relief team in Florida to avoid homes advertising President Trump. It is unacceptable to think that any American would be denied disaster aid on account of political alignment.

As Chairman of the Subcommittee on Government Operations and the Federal Workforce, I have been investigating FEMA disaster response throughout the country by hosting subcommittee hearings. I look forward to receiving answers from FEMA Director Criswell next week in a full @GOPoversight hearing.

Name: Mills, Cory
text:
After spending weeks evacuating people in the Carolinas and assisting with relief efforts in Florida, following Hurricanes Helene and Milton, I’ve learned that FEMA teams were directed in Florida to skip homes displaying Trump signs, with similar instructions reportedly given in the Carolinas.

This targeted discrimination is a clear abuse of government power and suggests a deeper, systemic issue within FEMA. While I fully support Governor DeSantis’ call for a deeper dive into FEMA’s practices here in Florida, given these new allegations, we need to determine how widespread this politicized behavior is within the agency.

As a reminder, President Biden dismissed concerns about FEMA, calling them “misinformation.” This situation highlights why the American people rejected the Biden-Harris administration, and we look forward to President Trump restoring accountability and transparency across our federal agencies.
